# SEO and Internal Linking

## Internal Linking Strategy
- Always link to related pages within the documentation when mentioning concepts, features, or topics covered elsewhere
- Use descriptive anchor text that clearly indicates what the linked page contains
- Create a wiki-like experience where users can easily navigate between related topics
- Link to both parent/overview pages and specific detailed pages as appropriate

## SEO Best Practices
- Use meaningful, descriptive headings (H1, H2, H3) that reflect the content hierarchy
- Include relevant keywords naturally in headings and content
- Write clear, concise meta descriptions for each page
- Use descriptive file names and URL slugs
- Ensure proper heading structure (don't skip heading levels)
- Add alt text to images that describes their content and purpose
- Use descriptive, keyword-rich page titles
- Create XML sitemaps
- Use structured data when applicable
- Ensure fast loading times
- Implement proper internal linking
- Use canonical URLs to avoid duplicate content

## Link Examples
- When mentioning "authentication", link to `/docs/authentication`
- When referencing "API endpoints", link to `/docs/api-reference`
- When discussing "configuration options", link to `/docs/configuration`
- Cross-reference related tutorials, guides, and reference materials

Remember: Every mention of a documented feature should be an opportunity to help users discover more relevant information.